Azure powershell - create VM
- launch PowerShell
- install the Azure PowerShell module
- sign in to your Azure account using the command 'Connect-AzAccount'
- and then issue a command such as:
New-AzVM `
    -ResourceGroupName "MyResourceGroup" `
    -Name "TestVm" `
    -Image "UbuntuLTS" `
    ...
    




Azure Powershell in azure cloud shell OR shell.azure.com
Pwsh -> load powershell
Get-azcontext -> check name, account id, subscription name, environment, tenantid
Get-azvm -> check AZ-VM combos -> resource group name, name, location, vmsize, OS, Provisioning State
    





Azure CLI - create VM
- open a command prompt window
- sign in to Azure using the command 'az login'
- create a resource group
- then use a command such as:
az vm create \
  --resource-group MyResourceGroup \
  --name TestVm \
  --image UbuntuLTS \
  --generate-ssh-keys \
  ...
  
  
